<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="compare_thermo_digt"><title>tutor</title><page><question id="q1"><body>Which of the following is involved in conserving heat?</body><multiple_choice select="single" shuffle="true"><choice value="A">sweating</choice><choice value="B">dilated blood vessels</choice><choice value="C">erect hair</choice><choice value="D">epithelial tissue</choice></multiple_choice><part id="i270015fd637947dfa980bd9632ecb1d8"><skillref idref="compare_thermo_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect. Sweating cools the body through evaporation.</feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect. Dilated blood vessels allow heat to escape and the body to cool.</feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback>Correct. Erect hair helps conserve heat by trapping air against the skin.</feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback>Incorrect. Adipose tissue will help conserve heat, not epithelial tissue.</feedback></response></part></question></page></assessment>
